[normal]I am John R. Christy, 
[normal]Distinguished 
[normal]Professor of Atmospheric Science, Alabama’s State Climatologist and Director of the Earth System Science Center at The University of Alabama in Huntsville.  I h
[normal]ave served as a Lead Author, 
[normal]Contributing Author
[normal] and Reviewer
[normal] of IPCC assessments,
[normal] have been awarded NASA’s Medal for Exceptional Scientific Achievement, and in 2002 
[normal]was 
[normal]elected a Fellow of the American Meteorological Society.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is a privil
[normal]ege for me to offer my views on the relationship between climate and weather 
[normal]based on my exper
[normal]ience as a climate scientist.  My research area might be best described as building datasets from scratch to advance our understanding of what the climate is doing and why. I have used traditional surface observations as well as measurements from balloons 
[normal]and satellites to document the climate story.  Many of my datasets are used to test hypotheses of climate variability and change.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Extreme[bold] Event[bold]s[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]As the glob
[normal]al temperature failed to warm over
[normal] the past 15 years, it became popular to 
[normal]draw
[normal] attention to the
[normal] occurrence of 
[normal]extreme weather 
[normal]events
[normal] as worrisome 
[normal]consequences
[normal] of 
[normal]postulated climate change due to 
[normal]increasing concentrations of greenhouse gases
[normal].  For example, m
[normal]any claims have been made that 
[normal]weather
[normal] events of the past 50 years are 
[normal]“
[normal]unprecedented
[normal]”
[normal], theref
[normal]ore must be caused by human influences
[normal].  However, o
[normal]ne can only
[normal] establish 
[normal]such events as 
[normal]statistically 
[normal]unusual
[normal], a lower standard than 
[normal]“
[normal]unprecedented,
[normal]”
[normal] if 
[normal]a minimum of
[normal] 30 or more
[normal] such periods with consistent data
[normal] are available
[normal].  This means
[normal] we need 1500 to 2000 years
[normal] of information
[normal] 
[normal]with which to compare our recent 50-years 
[normal]of history 
[normal]to determine whether any characteristic is 
[normal]truly 
[normal]unusual
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]For a few parameters we have such data.  Severe drought leaves a clear 
[normal]mark
[normal] on the 
[normal]landscape so th
[normal]at
[normal] we know our nation experienced droughts in the 12
[normal]th
[normal] century, the so-called mega
[normal]-
[normal]droughts, which were much worse than any we’ve seen in the past century.
[normal]  Thus, droughts of the past 50 years are not unusual 
[normal]and obviously not 
[normal]“
[normal]unprecedented
[normal]”
[normal] as shown next
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]California[bold]At right are photos from Lindstrom (1990) 
[normal]of divers examining 
[normal]trees 
[normal]which 
[normal]grew on dry ground around 900 years ago in what is now a Sierra Nevada alpine lake.  This indicates that a drastic but natural change to a much drier climate 
[normal]occurred a
[normal]nd must
[normal] have lasted for at least 
[normal]50 years
[normal] for trees to have grown to these sizes
[normal] on dry ground.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Rocky Mountains[bold]A 500-year history of moisture in the upper Colorado River basin (
[normal]below
[normal]) indicates the past century was quite moist while major multi-decadal droughts occurred in all four prior centuries (Piechota et al. 2004.)  Indeed, the conclusion of Piechota et al. states that after examining the paleo-record, the present-day droughts “
[normal]could be worse.” These and other evidences point to the real probability that water supply in the West will 
[normal]see declines simply as a matter of the natural variability of climate
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Great Plains[bold]In the Great Plains, the period from 3000 to 1500 
[normal]years ago
[normal] saw a drier and warmer climate during which a significant parabolic sand dune ecosystem developed, especially in western Nebraska and NE Colorado (Muhs 1985).
[normal]  In other words, 
[normal]parts of 
[normal]the Great Plains resembled a desert.
[normal]  Many of these areas experienced 
[normal]dune “reactivation” during Medieval times (900-1300 AD).  The
[normal]n, the
[normal] climate moistened and cooled 
[normal]beginning around
[normal] 1300 AD to support the short-grass prairie seen today, though “reactivation” is possible at any time (Schmeisser, 2009).  Indeed, Muhs and Hol
[normal]liday (1995) found that dune reactivation can occur within decadal time scales from extended drought by examining the Great Plains environmen
[normal]t of only the past 150 years. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]With the massive use of ground water for irrigation, the High Plains Aquifer has d
[normal]eclined an average of 12.8 ft, with some areas in the Texas panhandle down over 150 ft.   The key point here is that the Plains is subject to 
[normal]natural (and sobering) 
[normal]long-term droughts that would very likely tax the current water management system (ground-w
[normal]ater withdrawals) while not replenishing the aquifer, producing a situation of reduced agricultural productivity, especially in its southern reaches.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]U.S. [bold]Daily High Temperature Records[bold]Are daily high temperature extremes becoming more frequent?  To answe
[normal]r such a question, one must obviously consider datasets that span an appropriate length of time.  If one 
[normal]does
[normal] the analysis 
[normal]with
[normal] stations 
[normal]of
[normal] at least 80 years of data, and determines the number of daily temperature records by year that stand as of 31 Dec 20
[normal]12, the answer to the question is 
[normal]“
[normal]no.
[normal]”
[normal]  It is true that the number of records in 2012 was quite high, thanks to a very warm March and a hot Mid-Western summer.  However in comparison to the heat waves of the 1930s, the summer was not the “worst” for heat.
[normal]  
[normal]2012 finished in 8
[normal]th
[normal] place on the list, just below 
[normal]6
[normal]th
[normal] and 7
[normal]th
[normal] places
[normal] by a few days.
[normal]  Imagine what this diagram would show if we had 1000 years of climate data in which it 
[normal]would be 
[normal]certainly likely that many years experienced more record warmth than even
[normal] the 1930s.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Recent [bold]Tornadoes[bold]The image to the right from NOAA indicates we are in a very low
[normal] 
[normal]tornado period in our count
[normal]r
[normal]y – in fact the current year (
[normal]right, 
[normal]black line) is the lowest year-to-date (
[normal]Nov
[normal].) value in the 60-year history.  This of course is 
[normal]not a prediction that tornadoes will decline in the future nor that there will be few tornadoes the rest of this year.  It is simply a recognition that the number of tornadoes can vary significantly from year to year and there is no long term trend (
[normal]http://www.spc.noaa.gov/wcm/adj.html
[normal])
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Recent Wildfires[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Wildfires are a natural 
[normal]consequence
[normal] of the U.S. climate
[normal] variability
[normal] and a feature to which many components of the natural ecosystem have found ways 
[normal]for
[normal] advantage-
[normal]taking
[normal].  Nowadays however, our fire su
[normal]ppression activities that allow
[normal] 
[normal]e
[normal]xcessive buildup of fuel combined with the careless or premeditated human character of some folks, gives greater opportunity for wildfires to 
[normal]be started
[normal] and to destroy.  The 
[normal]current year has included the 
[normal]huge
[normal] Rim Fire in the central Sierra Nevada of California, but
[normal],
[normal] on the whole
[normal],
[normal] the year is well below average
[normal] as shown in the graphic to the 
[normal]above
[normal] (data from the National Interagency Fire Center 
[normal]http://www.nifc.gov/fireInfo/fireInfo_stats_totalFires.html
[normal])
[normal].
[normal]  A related metric is total snowfall in the Sierra
[normal] of California
[normal] which has 
[normal]also 
[normal]shown no trend since the Southern Pacific Railroad Company began measuri
[normal]ng snowfall in 1878 (Christy 2012).
[normal]West [bold]Antarctica [bold]Coastal[bold] Temperatures[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Temperatures over the vast expanse of the Antarctic continent have not shown significant warming in the past several decades.  Indeed satellite-based observations of the 
[normal]atmospheric temperature above Antarctica show a slight decline since 1979.  However, m
[normal]easurements along the coast of West Antarctic 
[normal]and its 
[normal]Peninsula have warmed in recent years.  Thomas et al. (2013) have reconstructed 308 years of temperature variations (1702-2009) through stable isotopes and confirmed the recent warming.  They found that
[normal],
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]… this warming trend is not unique.  More dramatic isotopic warming (and cooling) trends occurred in the mid-nineteenth and eighteenth centuries suggesting that at present, the effect of anthropogenic climate drivers at this location has not exceeded 
[normal]the natural range of climate variability in the context of the past ~300 years.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Here we have another example that indicates we must have hundreds of years of
[normal] climate records 
[normal]before 
[normal]trying to assess 
[normal]whether 
[normal]recent changes
[normal] are unusual
[normal].  In this case, the te
[normal]mperatures of West Antarc
[normal]tica have experienced similar and likely 
[normal]greater changes
[normal] than recently observed
[normal] in merely the las
[normal]t 300 years, a period before which humans could have affected the climate.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]What does Extreme Weather [bold]really tell us[bold]?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The point about
[normal] our 
[normal]lack of 
[normal]understanding 
[normal]of t
[normal]he causes of ext
[normal]reme weather was summed up in
[normal] an
[normal] article in 
[normal]Nature
[normal] magazine with the title “Extreme Weather – Better models are needed before exceptional events can be reliably linked to global warming” (
[normal]Nature
[normal], 20 September 
[normal]2012, vol 489, pg 335-6.) The emphasis in the article agrees with my statement that our level of understanding about the climate system is so low that we cannot predict nor attribute unusual events to human emissions of greenhouse gases
[normal] using models and/or
[normal] limited data records
[normal].  The article discusses the problem that current climate models are not “fit to inform legal and societal decisions” without further “enormous research” because at present they are not ready for such tasks.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The article notes that ext
[normal]reme events “have complex causes, involving anomalies in atmospheric circulation, levels of soil moisture and the like.”  The comments of one scientist at a recent workshop on the topic indicated “the coarse and mathematically far-from-perfect climate mode
[normal]ls used to generate attribution claims … are unjustifiably speculative, basically unverifiable and better not made at all.”  Not all participants felt this way, however 
[normal]Nature
[normal] reported that, “None of the industry and government experts at the workshop coul
[normal]d think of any concrete example in which an attribution might inform business or political decision-making.”  In other words, industry and government would prefer an accurate forecast over the notion of attributing that forecast to a particular cause.  Unf
[normal]ortunately, the ability to make accurate
[normal] long-range forecasts is not here yet
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In the examples above, we don’t see increases in extreme events (which is also true for tornadoes, hurricanes, floods, etc. - see my House testimony of 31 March 2011) but we mu
[normal]st certainly be ready for more to come as part of nature’s variability. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I am not using 
[normal]the examples above
[normal] to prove the weather in the US is becoming less extreme.  My point is that extreme events are poor metrics to use for detecting climate 
[normal]change.  In
[normal]deed, because of their rarity (by definition) using extreme events to bolster a claim about any type of climate change (warming or cooling) runs the risk of setting up the classic “non-falsifiable hypothesis.”    For example, we were told by the IPCC that 
[normal]“milder winter temperatures will decrease heavy snowstorms” (TAR WG2, 15.2.4.1.2.4).  After the winters of 2009-10 and 2010-11, we are told the opposite by advocates of the IPCC position, “Climate Change Makes Major Snowstorms More Likely” (
[normal]http://www.ucsusa.org/news/press_release/climate-change-makes-snowstorms-more-likely-0506.html
[normal]).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The non-falsifiable hypotheses can be stated this way, 
[normal]“whatever happens is consistent with my hypothesis.”  In other words, there is no event that would “falsify” the hypothesis.  As such, these assertions cannot be considered science
[normal],
[normal] or in anyway informative
[normal],
[normal] since the hypothesis’ fundamental prediction is 
[normal]“anything 
[normal]can
[normal] happen.”  In the example above if winters become milder or they become snowier, the non-falsifiable hypothesis stands.  This is not science.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There are innumerable types of events that can be defined as extreme events – so for the enterprisin
[normal]g individual (unencumbered by the scientific method), weather statistics can supply an unlimited, target-rich environment in which to discover a “useful” extreme event. Thus, when the enterprising individual observes an unusual weather event, it may be tem
[normal]pting to define it as a once-for-all extreme metric to “prove” a point about climate change – even if the event was measured at a station with only 30 years of record. Extreme events happen, and their causes are intricately tied to the semi-unstable dynami
[normal]cal situations that can occur out of an environment of natural, unforced variability.
[normal]  In other words, Mother Nature ha
[normal]s within her all the necessary tools
[normal] to generate extreme events that exceed what we’ve seen in the past 50 years.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Science checks hypothe
[normal]ses (assertions) by testing specific, falsifiable predictions implied by those hypotheses.  The predictions are to be made in a manner that, as much as possible, is blind to the data against which they are evaluated.  It is the testable predictions from
[normal] a 
[normal]specific set of
[normal] hypotheses, 
[normal]otherwise known as
[normal] 
[normal]climate model
[normal] simulation
[normal]s
[normal], that run into trouble as shown 
[normal]below
[normal].  Before going on to that test, the main point here is that extreme events do not lend themselves as being rigorous metrics for 
[normal]convicting
[normal] human 
[normal]CO2 emissions of being guilty of causing them.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Utility of Climate Models[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]In the f
[normal]igure
[normal] below
[normal] 
[normal]I provide the 35-
[normal]year record 
[normal](1979-2013) 
[normal]of 
[normal]atmospheric temperature in the tropics – the key region in which climate models respond to greenhouse gas warming wit
[normal]h a large and distinct signal. 
[normal] The focus on the tropics is important because 
[normal]of the consistent and significant warming that climate models indicate should have already occurred as a result of the increasing concentration of greenhouse gases w
[normal]e have put i
[normal]nto the atmosphere. 
[normal]  
[normal]It also represents a part of the global atmosphere in which the critical water vapor and cloud feedbacks have major influences.
[normal]  In addition, changes in this region were determined by the EPA to be a 
[normal]key line of evidence of
[normal] greenhouse-gas caused climate change.  Finally, t
[normal]he tropical atmosphere is also a huge and easy target for modeling projects to hit if the physics are well represented.  
[normal]Since this warming should have taken place already, this provides for us a way to tes
[normal]t the model simulations.
[normal] There are 102 model runs represented in the figure, but I have organized them by the 
[normal]24 types of models
[normal].  The thick red line is the average of the 24 groups.  Thin, solid lines are the six model groupings created by U.S. institutio
[normal]ns and the dotted 
[normal]lines 
[normal]by those 
[normal]from 
[normal]outside the U.S.  The observations are provided by six independent 
[normal]sources
[normal], 
[normal]with “balloons” being the average of the 
[normal]four balloon-borne 
[normal]datasets
[normal] and 
[normal]“satellites” the average of the two 
[normal]groups which utilize satellite in
[normal]strumentation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The comparison
[normal] shows 
[normal]t
[normal]hat the very latest climate model simulations 
[normal]used in the IPCC Assessment released two 
[normal]months
[normal] ago 
[normal]indicate that their response to CO2 on average is 2 to 
[normal]5
[normal] times greater than reality. 
[normal]  In strict statistical testing, we can say that the m
[normal]odels on average failed a simple
[normal] hypothesis test 
[normal]to check whether they could represent
[normal] the path the real world took on tropical 
[normal]atmospheric 
[normal]temperatures
[normal] (see Douglass et
[normal] al. 2007, McKitrick et al. 2010,
[normal] 2011
[normal], Douglass and Christy 2013)
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]An 
[normal]extremely important
[normal] paper was published in 
[normal]Nature Climate Change
[normal] this past spring as one of the first 
[normal]studies 
[normal]to actually perform a test of model capabilities 
[normal]in a controlled experiment to
[normal] understand the impacts on the critical processes that affect the way 
[normal]the temperature will change
[normal] (Stephens and Bony, 2013)
[normal].  They simply ran 
[normal]four major climate models
[normal] 
[normal]over
[normal] an ocean-covered earth (i.e. a very simple earth) with the current ocean temperatur
[normal]es, then again with elevated ocean temperatures.  The experiment would then reveal the impact of the extra warmth on the way the climate system operates
[normal], especially, clouds and rain because they have significant impacts on the warming processes. So, gettin
[normal]g 
[normal]clouds and rain
[normal] correct is necessary for long-term integrations. 
[normal]To their surprise, the four major models gave quite different results
[normal] (figure above)
[normal], both in terms of
[normal] the
[normal] magnitude 
[normal]and of the sign
[normal] of the change in clouds 
[normal]and
[normal] rain as shown in the figure.
[normal] 
[normal]This is exactly the type of fundamental, rigorous evaluation that must be encouraged for other parts of the modeling enterprise.  One can only conclude that at least three of the four models fail (if on the
[normal] odd
[normal] ch
[normal]ance o
[normal]ne is correct) to depict
[normal] the
[normal] fundame
[normal]ntal 
[normal]process
[normal]es
[normal] of the Earth system.  This result supports the comments in the paragraphs above which demonstrate the climate modeling enterprise must go “
[normal]back to the
[normal] basics” as stated in Stephens and Bony.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In a paper published last week
[normal], 
[normal]Swanson (2013) ex
[normal]amined the previous generation of climate models used in the IPCC AR4 (
[normal]2007, 
[normal]known as CMIP3) in comparison with the latest generation of models employed in the current IPCC AR5 (known as CMIP5 models as I used earlier).  Swanson found that the newer CMIP5 
[normal]models were worse at depicting actual climate 
[normal]variations 
[normal]than the older CMIP3 versions.  He suggests that the modelers have a “selection bias based on warming rate” that attempts to replicate the rapid warming of the Arctic (a small region) while becoming 
[normal]worse (too warm) in the much more vast tropics and southern hemisphere.
[normal]  He argues for a “healthy dose
[normal] of diversity” to be reintroduced into the climate simulation enterprise.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Basing scientific conclusions about climate change 
[normal](
[normal]or 
[normal]basing 
[normal]policy decisions 
[normal]about energy
[normal])
[normal] on 
[normal]climate 
[normal]model output is risky given the 
[normal]inability of
[normal] model simulations 
[normal]to reproduce the real
[normal] world – and their results are not getting better.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The IPCC Summary for Policy Makers[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Regarding the IPCC, please note that the IPCC was written by IPCC-selected scientists and that the document represents their opinions.  Many of the conclusions are fine but some of the key ones do not represent the views of 
[normal]many in 
[normal]the broader climate comm
[normal]unity.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The head
[normal]line statement from the
[normal] 2013
[normal] 
[normal]Summary for Policy Makers
[normal] baffles me.  It reads,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is extremely likely that human influence has been the dominant cause of the observed warming since the mid-20
[normal]th
[normal] century.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]First, the IPCC 
[normal]relies on
[normal] climate 
[normal]models to distinguish “natural” from “human” caused climate change because instruments can’t.  However, as demonstrated, these same models on average fail 
[normal]by a significant amount 
[normal]to reproduce the climate of the past 35 years
[normal] (the years most directly impact
[normal]ed by rising greenhouse gas emissions
[normal].
[normal])
[normal]  But in conclusion, the IPCC now has
[normal] even
[normal] more confidence that the models can distinguish “natural” from 
[normal]“human” change
[normal] 
[normal]over a period the models clearly fail to simulate well
[normal].  It doesn’t make sense to me.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Now, i
[normal]t
[normal] is true that 
[normal]in the models
[normal], most of the warming in the past 50 years is due to greenhouse gases, but since the model-based warming did not occur in reality (by a significant amount), how can one claim that reality was driven by greenhouse gas warming?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I 
[normal]see two things here, (1) 
[normal]the
[normal] need to go back to the drawing board on climate modeling 
[normal]with special attention to the causes of natural variations and 
[normal]with a rigorously independent 
[normal]validation
[normal] program
[normal] (i.e. a
[normal] set of relatively inexpensive but
[normal] true “
[normal]Red Team[bold]s[bold]”)
[normal], and (2) the world community needs to be exposed to the real debates in climate science rather than statements amounting to a consensus of those who already agree with a
[normal] certain
[normal] consensus.
[normal]  These are sentiments I have been advocating for years
[normal] in congre
[normal]ssional testimony
[normal] and
[normal] which
[normal] appear in an article published in 
[normal]Nature
[normal] magazine (Christy, 
[normal]2010
[normal] see after references
[normal]).
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In addition, 
[normal]I direct 
[normal]the reader
[normal] to 
[normal]a supplement attached
[normal] to 
[normal]this
[normal] written testimony by Professor Judith Curry of Georgia Tech entitled, “IPCC Diagnosis – Permanent Paradigm Paralysis.”
[normal]  The title is an apt description of where the IPCC process has gone.
