[normal]Seventeen Years Ago – House Committee on Science[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Seventeen years 
[normal]ago, in March 1996, I testified before this committee 
[normal]regarding
[normal] climate change. In that testimony I reported on the development of the deep layer 
[normal]atmospheric 
[normal]temperature datasets 
[normal]from satellites 
[normal]that Roy Spencer, then of NASA
[normal] now of UAHuntsville
[normal], and I had
[normal] pioneered.  Using these data
[normal],
[normal] Richard McNider, also of UAHuntsville, and I wrote a paper in 
[normal]Nature
[normal] magazine that indicated climate model simulations were warming the planet about 4 times faster than in reality (Christy and McNider 1994).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Further analysis
[normal] confirmed a
[normal] rate in models
[normal] 2 to 4 times 
[normal]faster than the
[normal] real world
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It was clear at the time, and agreed to by 
[normal]nearly everyone
[normal], that our understanding
[normal] of how the climate system worked
[normal] was poor and much more research was needed on observing the climate and on understanding its natural variations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] I also noted that we should expect weather extremes 
[normal]to continue 
[normal]because that has been the nature of climate from the beginning. 
[normal]One of my c
[normal]oncludin
[normal]g statements was, and I quote, 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Without a continuing program of research that places climate variations in proper perspective
[normal] 
[normal][i.e. 
[normal]natural climate variations
[normal]]
[normal] and reports with improving confidence on their causes, we will be vulnerable to calls f
[normal]or knee-jerk remedies to combat "climate change," which likely will be unproduc
[normal]tive and economically damaging.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Now here we are, over 17 years later.  It appears the nation has indeed enacted “knee-jerk” remedies to 
[normal]“combat climate change”
[normal] through regulat
[normal]ions on carbon dioxide.  I warned
[normal] this committee
[normal] in 1996 that these would be “unproductive and economically damaging.” I have since provided testimony that demonstrates that these regulations will be “unproductive” regarding their impact on climate.  I wil
[normal]l leave it to economists to determine whether the regulations
[normal] which result in higher energy prices
[normal] are also “economically damaging”, especially for the poorest among us.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The nation did 
[normal]indeed 
[normal]support
[normal] some
[normal] efforts to 
[normal]improve the
[normal] 
[normal]climate 
[normal]observ
[normal]ing
[normal] system, e
[normal]specially from space, 
[normal]to help in determining
[normal] 
[normal]what 
[normal]was happening with the climate, and then begin to understand 
[normal]why
[normal] changes are taking place.  Other efforts seem to be falling by the wayside
[normal],
[normal] including attention to the network of high quality surface monito
[normal]ring stations
[normal] such as NOAA’s Regional Climate Reference Network
[normal].  Simply put, we need to know 
[normal]what
[normal] the climate 
[normal]i
[normal]s doing before claiming to know 
[normal]why
[normal] it 
[normal]is doing what it i
[normal]s doing
[normal].  W
[normal]ithout 
[normal]accurate 
[normal]observations we 
[normal]can
[normal] not know 
[normal]what
[normal] the climate is doing
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is 
[normal]enlightening
[normal] to examine the
[normal] 35-
[normal]year comparison of models and observations of atmospheric temperature in the tropics – the key region in which climate models respond to greenhouse gas warming with a large and distinct signal
[normal] and a region promoted by t
[normal]he EPA as a fingerprint of human-induced climate change
[normal].
[normal]  This is an exceptionally large target for climate models to aim at, and it incorporates the critical water vapor and cloud feedbacks about which we know so little.   The current
[normal] record is now twice 
[normal]as long as was available when I testified in 1996 and the models are more complicate
[normal]d, expensive and numerous
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]representing
[normal] an industry unto itself
[normal].  The comparison
[normal] 
[normal]shows that the very latest climate models’
[normal] 
[normal]tropical 
[normal]response to CO2
[normal],
[normal] on average
[normal],
[normal] is still 2
[normal] to 
[normal]5
[normal] times greater than reality
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]just 
[normal]as 
[normal]it was
[normal] in 1996. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I believe we missed a tremendous opportunity 
[normal]17 years ago
[normal] to develop a better understanding 
[normal]of the climate system 
[normal]because
[normal] research dollars
[normal] were directed
[normal] to
[normal] 
[normal]establish
[normal] a climate
[normal] modeling industry
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]To 
[normal]compound the problem
[normal] as it developed
[normal], I believe
[normal] we
[normal] failed to
[normal] fund substantial projects to
[normal] examine the output of climate models in an independent, objective and method
[normal]ological
[normal] 
[normal]way, i.e. 
[normal]we did not establish “red teams”
[normal] to rigorously study the output of m
[normal]odels on which the most expensive of regulations 
[normal]now 
[normal]rely.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]This 
[normal]has left us 
[normal]17 years later 
[normal]still wondering
[normal] 
[normal]what porti
[normal]on of th
[normal]e 
[normal]recent modest 
[normal]change
[normal] 
[normal]is
[normal] natural and what portion might be
[normal] human-caused.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Conclusion[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]In this testimony,
[normal] evidence is presented to demonstrate that recent weather events are not outside the extremes that have occurred in the past 
[normal]when human influences were negligible
[normal].  Therefore
[normal] in my view
[normal] one cannot
[normal] 
[normal]attribute 
[normal]these recent events
[normal] 
[normal]with any confidence 
[normal]to
[normal] someth
[normal]ing 
[normal]beyond nature.  Climate models are 
[normal]promoted as tools that are able
[normal] to discriminate 
[normal]natural climate events
[normal] versus 
[normal]those that
[normal] might happen as a result of the increases in greenhouse gases due to human activities
[normal] and have been used by EPA for regulatory a
[normal]ction
[normal].  Unfortunately, as demonstrated here
[normal] and discussed in the literature
[normal], climate models have not demonstrated acceptable skill in terms of depicting
[normal] even
[normal] 
[normal]very 
[normal]fundamental, large-scale climate variations, and thus are unable to identify natural versus human-influenced events on regional scales.  Indeed, the lack of modeling skill regarding very basic processes such as tropical tropospheric variations, indica
[normal]tes that the modeling enterprise has not been subject to rigorous, independent “Red Team” oversight during its expensive growth 
[normal]period.  In addition,
[normal] significant advancements are needed in observing and understanding the natural processes of climate before
[normal] reliable, though basic, forecasts are forthcoming.   
[normal]It is unfortunate
[normal], in my opinion,
[normal] that recent policy has been made based on the projections of these faulty models.  
[normal]Climate science has a long way to go.
